34:05.916 --> 34:14.608
fellas and selecting along with Professor 
Samuel, Professor Eli Samuel. He's dead now, but

34:14.668 --> 34:17.232
he's a magnificent man. And he was the sort of fella 
that'd give me responsibilities.

34:24.122 --> 34:43.063
He allowed me to take his car, for example, and take 
five or six of the key Future Farmers of America

34:24.122 --> 34:43.063
from Sanger, all of which is 50 miles north of here, 
all the way down to Texas A&M, meet him down there.

34:43.103 --> 34:44.965
He'd drive somebody else's car. He'd give me that 
responsibility. He was a professor at A&M. He was a

34:49.869 --> 34:52.292
later professor at A&M. He was a professor there 
and the superintendent of the school, a singer. So

34:58.619 --> 35:03.224
he was an influential fellow in my life. And

35:03.244 --> 35:14.877
it's that sort of thing that brought this on. Did 
you consider yourself popular in high school?

35:17.542 --> 35:20.065
Were you popular with the other students? Yes, I 
think so. I don't know of any enemies I had.

35:26.853 --> 35:31.479
Sometimes you have some, you don't know it, you 
know, but most of the time you know who they are. But

35:33.101 --> 35:35.043
as far as I know, I had none. When you graduated from 
high school, did you have firm aims about what you

35:35.064 --> 35:39.309
wanted to do? I mean, had you made up your mind, I 
want to go to A&M or? Did you think maybe military

35:42.515 --> 35:48.583
academy or just what did you think when you 
graduated? Well, my dad wanted me to be a doctor of

35:49.965 --> 35:53.029
veterinary medicine.

35:57.334 --> 36:00.759
And we had no money for me to go to school on. Zero. We 
never lacked for food or clothing or anything like

36:03.282 --> 36:06.506
that.

36:09.270 --> 36:11.593
And didn't have any debts. But when you make a 
bumper crop of oats or wheat and you

36:12.940 --> 36:37.486
sell it at the end of the year at the harvest time and 
it just barely pays the fuel bill and doesn't even

36:12.940 --> 36:37.486
pay you for your labor and so on and so forth, how can 
you send a guy that takes his A&M even if it's only

36:12.940 --> 36:37.486
for $5 a year? How do you do it? Well, I'll tell you 
how you do it. Mr. Samuel, Professor Samuel is

36:43.788 --> 36:55.160
interested enough in your capabilities and what 
he sees in you that he assists you in getting a job. I

36:57.762 --> 37:11.196
went to North Texas Agricultural College out here 
for one year and got off a few credits, but I worked

36:57.762 --> 37:11.196
the whole time I was there. Then I wanted to go to 
A&M. So this was kind of a prep school up here. I

37:19.308 --> 37:21.170
worked most of the time. And then Mr. Samuels 
helped me get a job at Texas A&M in the creamery down

37:21.270 --> 37:34.128
there across the tracks. And I had done real well in 
freshman chemistry. like that sort of stuff. And

37:44.481 --> 37:48.928
first thing you knew, I became the lab technician 
there. Well, what does that encompass? That

37:53.234 --> 38:09.637
encompass getting up at four o'clock in the 
morning

37:53.234 --> 38:09.637
and start sampling milk coming into that plant 
down there from all over Brazos County and so

37:53.234 --> 38:09.637
forth. Sampling that milk and then going and 
running the chemical analysis tests on it and then

38:12.517 --> 38:42.456
getting that out promptly and giving it to the 
farmer who's standing by as to what his bacterial

38:12.517 --> 38:42.456
count was or whatever the fat content was usually 
the fat content I run the bacterial count a little

38:12.517 --> 38:42.456
later because you know you had to cultivate that a 
little bit and uh but he has to know what what the

38:42.723 --> 39:11.413
butterfat content is because that's what you're 
going to pay him per hundred weight on and I had to do

38:42.723 --> 39:11.413
that while he was while his truck was waiting and 
get that on a piece of paper and our and they finally

38:42.723 --> 39:11.413
all got in about uh uh 7 45 then I had to run take a 
shower and made an 8 10 class

38:42.723 --> 39:11.413
and then in the afternoon uh It was four o'clock

39:11.748 --> 39:18.178
after school. We finished up about 830. That's how 
much I had to work in order to stay down there. I

39:29.577 --> 39:33.162
think we got 20 cents an hour or something. I'm not 
sure what it was.

39:38.714 --> 39:41.257
So you usually put in about eight hours a day. I 
worked eight hours a day and tried to take 16

39:41.277 --> 40:07.303
credits and I'd bust the hell out of English and do 
well on the other subjects and when I finished off

39:41.277 --> 40:07.303
down there I lacked one or two grade points of being 
able to go up and get my diploma and so they deferred

39:41.277 --> 40:07.303
my my diploma for one year because I was short a 
couple of grade points, but that didn't bother me a

40:08.718 --> 40:19.192
damn bit. They couldn't treat me harshly because 
I'd learned a hell of a lot. It was a great hardship,

40:27.903 --> 40:37.375
and I'd learned the preciseness that my father had 
taught me was not in the subjects and the manner in

40:38.384 --> 40:50.680
which the professors had puttin' it across, but 
was in the hardships that I'd suffered in order to

40:38.384 --> 40:50.680
stay in down there, and the military. Did they send 
you your diploma the next year, then? Yes. Yes.

40:57.148 --> 41:00.072
They sent me my diploma the next year. That's all 
right. I don't mind that. No. Hellfire. Did you

41:03.957 --> 41:07.902
ever think about going or applying for West Point? 
I

41:08.658 --> 41:35.425
guess that that was so far away, and for a farm guy to 
do that, that was just beyond my capabilities at

41:08.658 --> 41:35.425
that time to even apply.

41:42.998 --> 41:51.530
I was happy, though, when West Point selected me as 
the first non-West Point graduate to go back there

41:42.998 --> 41:51.530
as an instructor.

41:54.875 --> 42:02.705
Did the fact that we had a Corps of Cadets have 
anything to do with your deciding to go to A&M? Yes,

42:02.725 --> 42:03.366
it did. Will you explain?

42:08.674 --> 42:10.997
I was here at— NTHC, they had North Texas 
Agricultural College.

42:19.550 --> 42:23.116
You could either join the ROTC or not.

42:26.621 --> 42:41.001
And I watched,

42:26.621 --> 42:41.001
I watched

42:26.621 --> 42:41.001
for about a week these fellows all in the same 
uniform and They were doing things together, and

42:42.432 --> 42:53.026
they had a leader out there, and they had junior 
leaders.

42:55.990 --> 43:11.832
I said to myself,

42:55.990 --> 43:11.832
that's the sort of thing that would really be nice 
if I could progress up to be a leader of those guys

42:55.990 --> 43:11.832
there.

43:15.929 --> 43:26.698
I haven't seen anything else around here that's 
demanding from the standpoint of somebody being

43:15.929 --> 43:26.698
in charge and people reacting.

43:30.301 --> 43:45.514
And I knew they had a big corps of cadets at Texas 
A&M, and I thought the bigger the cadet corps, the

43:30.301 --> 43:45.514
better chance you've got of progressing up to some 
leadership.

43:48.346 --> 43:51.611
And I think that's what inspired me more to go to 
A&M. So it was a combination of the military and the

43:51.671 --> 43:55.898
desire to be a veterinarian? Yes, and my father was 
pushing me on the veterinarian business, but when

43:56.920 --> 44:16.210
I got out of A&M, I looked at this business of five 
years and studying, and there was just no way that I

43:56.920 --> 44:16.210
could stay in school down there and work, and

44:17.000 --> 44:27.976
ever become a doctor of veterinary medicine. I 
mean, the requirements are very demanding,

44:29.037 --> 44:41.455
and you've got to be able to put forth time to study. 
And, hell, when did I study?

44:52.623 --> 44:56.348
When do you study if you're working seven or eight 
hours a day?

44:59.311 --> 45:00.172
When do you do that? Let me tell you what you've got 
to do. You've got to somehow or another,

45:04.017 --> 45:11.526
regardless of how little sleep and how tired you 
are, you've got to stay awake. in class and listen

45:12.046 --> 45:23.384
and make notes on everything and be able to read the 
notes after you make them.

45:23.404 --> 45:24.426
That's what you've got to do.

45:27.351 --> 45:34.442
And you've got to have a book and you've got to, when 
somebody else wants to go out and play some

45:27.351 --> 45:34.442
softball or something, Whenever it is you've got 
some free time, you've got to thumb through those

45:35.249 --> 45:46.992
books and inspect these things and pick out what 
you think is important. And sometimes you miss.

